{"title_page": "Smash Hits", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox Magazine\n| title              = Smash Hits\n| image_file         = Department S - Smash Hits May 1981 magazine cover.jpg\n| image_size         = 175px\n| image_caption      = Cover of a 1988 edition of ''Smash Hits'' featuring [[Kylie Minogue]] and [[Jason Donovan]] as cover.\n| company            = [[EMAP|EMAP Metro]] (original)<br>[[Bauer Media Group]] (one-off specials)\n| paid_circulation   = \n| unpaid_circulation = \n| total_circulation  = \n| circulation_year   = \n| language           = English\n| category           = A4-size music magazine\n| frequency          = Initially monthly, then fortnightly\n| editor             = \n| firstdate          = {{start date and age|1978|9}};<br>{{start date and age|2009|7}} (one-off specials)\n| lastdate           = {{end date and age|2006|2|13}} (final regular issue);<br>{{end date and age|2019|11}} (final one-off special)\n| country            = United Kingdom\n| website            = \n| issn               = 0260-3004\n}}\n\n'''''Smash Hits''''' was a British [[music magazine]] aimed at young adults, originally published by [[EMAP]]. It ran from 1978 to 2006,<ref>{{cite book|author1=Di Hand|author2=Steve Middleditch|title=Design for Media: A Handbook for Students and Professionals in Journalism, PR, and Advertising|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UrAABAAAQBAJ&pg=PA8|accessdate=2 August 2015|date=10 July 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-86402-8|page=8}}</ref> and after initially appearing monthly, was issued [[fortnight]]ly during most of that time. The name survived as a brand for a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] [[Smash Hits (TV channel)|digital television channel]], now named Box Hits, and website. A [[Smash Hits Radio|digital radio station]] was also available but closed on 5 August 2013.\n\n== Overview ==\n''Smash Hits'' featured the lyrics of latest hits and interviews with big names in music. It was initially published monthly, then went fortnightly. The style of the magazine was initially serious, but from around the mid-1980s onwards became one of ever-increasing irreverence. Its interviewing technique was novel at the time and, rather than looking up to the big names, it often made fun of them, asking strange questions rather than talking about their music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2018/aug/06/how-we-made-smash-hits-magazine|title=How we made Smash Hits magazine|last=Simpson|first=Dave|date=2018-08-06|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2016/08/17/12-reasons-smash-hits-was-the-best-music-magazine-ever-6057584/|title=12 reasons Smash Hits was the best music magazine ever|date=2016-08-17|work=Metro|access-date=2018-10-22|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nCreated by journalist Nick Logan, the title was launched in 1978 and appeared monthly for its first few months. He based the idea on a songwords magazine that his sister used to buy, but which was of poor quality. His idea being to launch a glossy-looking magazine which also contained songwords as its mainstay. The publisher was Emap, which was a small-time publisher based in [[Peterborough]] and the magazine was originally titled ''Disco Fever'', before they settled on ''Smash Hits''.<ref name=takethat>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/can-smash-hits-survive-the-end-of-take-that-1319556.html|title=Can 'Smash Hits' survive the end of Take That?|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-10-23|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n''Smash Hits'' launched the career of many journalists including [[Radio Times]] editor [[Mark Frith]]. Other well-known writers have included [[Dave Rimmer]], [[Mark Ellen]] (who went on to launch ''[[Q magazine|Q]]'', ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' and ''[[The Word (magazine)|Word]]''), [[Steve Beebee]], [[Chris Heath]], [[Tom Hibbert]] and [[Miranda Sawyer]]. [[Neil Tennant]] of the [[Pet Shop Boys]] also worked as a writer and assistant editor, and once claimed that had he not become a pop star, he would likely have pursued his ambition to become editor.\n\nThe magazine was also available in Continental Europe, especially in Germany where the issues could be bought at train stations or airports, whilst the title was licensed for a French version in the 1990s. There were other licensed versions in the magazine's history. In 1984, an Australian version was created and proved just as successful for that new market as the original had back in Britain, whilst in the United States, a version was published during the 1980s under the title ''[[Star Hits]]'', drawing articles from the British version.\n\nIt was published by [[Emap]], who also use the name for one of their [[digital television]] services, and for a [[digital radio]] station. The brand also covered the annual ''[[Smash Hits Poll Winners Party]]'', an awards ceremony voted for by readers of the magazine.\n\nThe magazine's sales peaked during the late 1980s. In the early part of the decade it was regularly selling 500,000 copies per issue, which had risen to over one million by 1989. Sales began to drop during the 1990s and by 1996 it was reported that sales were dropping roughly 100,000 per year.<ref name=takethat/> By the time of its demise, it was down to 120,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4673136.stm|title=Smash Hits magazine closing down|date=2006-02-02|access-date=2018-10-22|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Final years of publishing==\nIn the 1990s, the magazine's circulation slumped and it was overtaken by the [[BBC]]'s spin off magazine ''[[Top of the Pops (magazine)|Top of the Pops]]''. [[Emap]]'s other biweekly teen magazine of the period ''[[Big! Magazine|Big!]]'' (which featured more celebrities and stars of TV series including Australians based ''[[Home and Away]]'' and United States imported ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]'') was closed and this celeb focus was shifted over to ''Smash Hits'', which became less focused on [[teen pop]] and more of an entertainment magazine. The magazine also shifted size a number of times in subsequent relaunches including one format that was as big as an album with songwords to be clipped out on the card cover. Television presenter and journalist [[Kate Thornton]] was editor for a short time.\n\nIn February 2006, it was announced that the magazine would cease publication after the February 13 edition due to declining sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4673136.stm|title=Smash Hits magazine closing down|work=BBC News|date=2 February 2006|accessdate=22 March 2014}}</ref> The digital music video channel, digital radio, and website services still continue.\n\nIn July 2009, a one-off commemorative issue of the magazine was published as a tribute to singer [[Michael Jackson]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090706131423/http://uk.news.yahoo.com/21/20090703/ten-smash-hits-resurrected-for-jackson-5f8abb3.html Smash Hits resurrected for Jackson], ''[[Yahoo|Yahoo News]]'', Retrieved 4 July 2009</ref> Further one-off specials were released in November 2009 ([[Take That]]), December 2010 ([[Lady Gaga]])<ref>[http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1043483&c=1 Smash Hits returns for GaGa special] ''Music Week''.</ref> and November 2019 ([[Max Martin]]), the latter was a free magazine at certain [[London Underground]] stations to mark the debut of Martin's West End musical ''[[& Juliet]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bauermedia.co.uk/newsroom/press-releases/smash-hits-returns-a-one-off-special-of-the-iconic-music-magazine-to-be-published|title=SMASH HITS RETURNS: A ONE-OFF SPECIAL OF THE ICONIC MUSIC MAGAZINE TO BE PUBLISHED|work=[[Bauer Media Group]]|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Editors ==\n\n*\"Chris Hall\" (pseudonym of Nick Logan, who refused to use his name as editor, instead inventing the name from those of his children, Christian and Hallie)\n*Ian Cranna\n*[[David Hepworth]]\n*[[Mark Ellen]]\n*Steve Bush\n*[[Barry McIlheney]]\n*Richard Lowe\n*Mike Soutar\n*Mark Frith\n*[[Kate Thornton]]\n*Gavin Reeve\n*John McKie\n*[[Emma Jones (journalist)|Emma Jones]]\n*Lisa Smosarski\n*Lara Palamoudian\n\n==Compilation albums==\n[[EMAP]] licensed the brand for a number of compilation albums, including a tie in with the ''[[Now That's What I Call Music]]'' brand for ''[[Now Smash Hits]]'', a retrospective of the early 1980s (80 - 87).\n\n==Australian edition==\nThe Australian edition of ''Smash Hits'' magazine began in November 1984 as a fortnightly. The magazine blended some content from the parent publication with locally generated material. Australian ''Smash Hits'' was originally published by [[Fairfax Media|Fairfax Magazines]] and was later purchased by Mason Stewart Publications. Over the years it became a monthly and then a bi-monthly. In 2007 the magazine retailed for [[Australian dollar|A$]]5.95 Inc. [[Goods and Services Tax (Australia)|GST]] and [[New Zealand dollar|NZ$]]6.50. On 30 March 2007 it was announced that the Australian edition would cease publication due to low readership.<ref>[http://www.bandt.com.au/news/11/0c04af11.asp Emap - Emap shuts Smash Hits after 23 years<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214021938/http://www.bandt.com.au/news/11/0c04af11.asp |date=14 February 2009 }}</ref> The editor at that time was Emma Bradshaw. The issue that was scheduled to be released on 9 May 2007 was cancelled.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Smash Hits (TV channel)]]\n* [[The Hits]]\n* ''[[Number One (magazine)|Number One]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/arts/features/story/0,,1701290,00.html ''Guardian'' Culture Vulture on the demise of ''Smash Hits'']\n\n[[Category:1978 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2006 disestablishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British music magazines]]\n[[Category:Bauer Group (UK)]]\n[[Category:British biweekly magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1978]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 2006]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox Magazine\n| title              = Smash Hits\n| image_file         = Department S - Smash Hits May 1981 magazine cover.jpg\n| image_size         = 175px\n| image_caption      = Cover of a 1988 edition of ''Smash Hits'' featuring [[Kylie Minogue]] and [[Jason Donovan]] as cover.\n| company            = [[EMAP|EMAP Metro]] (original)<br>[[Bauer Media Group]] (one-off specials)\n| paid_circulation   = \n| unpaid_circulation = \n| total_circulation  = \n| circulation_year   = \n| language           = English\n| category           = A4-size music magazine\n| frequency          = Initially monthly, then fortnightly\n| editor             = \n| firstdate          = {{start date and age|1978|9}};<br>{{start date and age|2009|7}} (one-off specials)\n| lastdate           = {{end date and age|2006|2|13}} (final regular issue);<br>{{end date and age|2019|11}} (final one-off special)\n| country            = United Kingdom\n| website            = \n| issn               = 0260-3004\n}}\n\n'''''Smash Hits''''' was a British Teen /pop music magazine aimed at young adults, that was originally published by [[EMAP]]. It ran from 1978 to 2006<ref>{{cite book|author1=Di Hand|author2=Steve Middleditch|title=Design for Media: A Handbook for Students and Professionals in Journalism, PR, and Advertising|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UrAABAAAQBAJ&pg=PA8|accessdate=2 August 2015|date=10 July 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-86402-8|page=8}}</ref> and, after initially appearing monthly, was issued [[fortnight]]ly during most of that time. The name survived as a brand for a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] [[Smash Hits (TV channel)|digital television channel]], now named Box Hits, and website. A [[Smash Hits Radio|digital radio station]] was also available but closed on 5 August 2013.\n\n== Overview ==\n''Smash Hits'' featured the lyrics of latest hits and interviews with big names in music. It was initially published monthly, then went fortnightly. The style of the magazine was initially serious, but from around the mid-1980s onwards became one of ever-increasing irreverence. Its interviewing technique was novel at the time and, rather than looking up to the big names, it often made fun of them, asking strange questions rather than talking about their music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2018/aug/06/how-we-made-smash-hits-magazine|title=How we made Smash Hits magazine|last=Simpson|first=Dave|date=2018-08-06|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2016/08/17/12-reasons-smash-hits-was-the-best-music-magazine-ever-6057584/|title=12 reasons Smash Hits was the best music magazine ever|date=2016-08-17|work=Metro|access-date=2018-10-22|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nCreated by journalist Nick Logan, the title was launched in 1978 and appeared monthly for its first few months. He based the idea on a songwords magazine that his sister used to buy, but which was of poor quality. His idea being to launch a glossy-looking magazine which also contained songwords as its mainstay. The publisher was Emap, which was a small-time publisher based in [[Peterborough]] and the magazine was originally titled ''Disco Fever'', before they settled on ''Smash Hits''.<ref name=takethat>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/can-smash-hits-survive-the-end-of-take-that-1319556.html|title=Can 'Smash Hits' survive the end of Take That?|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-10-23|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n''Smash Hits'' launched the career of many journalists including [[Radio Times]] editor [[Mark Frith]]. Other well-known writers have included [[Dave Rimmer]], [[Mark Ellen]] (who went on to launch ''[[Q magazine|Q]]'', ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' and ''[[The Word (magazine)|Word]]''), [[Steve Beebee]], [[Chris Heath]], [[Tom Hibbert]] and [[Miranda Sawyer]]. [[Neil Tennant]] of the [[Pet Shop Boys]] also worked as a writer and assistant editor, and once claimed that had he not become a pop star, he would likely have pursued his ambition to become editor.\n\nThe magazine was also available in Continental Europe, especially in Germany where the issues could be bought at train stations or airports, whilst the title was licensed for a French version in the 1990s. There were other licensed versions in the magazine's history. In 1984, an Australian version was created and proved just as successful for that new market as the original had back in Britain, whilst in the United States, a version was published during the 1980s under the title ''[[Star Hits]]'', drawing articles from the British version.\n\nIt was published by [[Emap]], who also use the name for one of their [[digital television]] services, and for a [[digital radio]] station. The brand also covered the annual ''[[Smash Hits Poll Winners Party]]'', an awards ceremony voted for by readers of the magazine.\n\nThe magazine's sales peaked during the late 1980s. In the early part of the decade it was regularly selling 500,000 copies per issue, which had risen to over one million by 1989. Sales began to drop during the 1990s and by 1996 it was reported that sales were dropping roughly 100,000 per year.<ref name=takethat/> By the time of its demise, it was down to 120,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4673136.stm|title=Smash Hits magazine closing down|date=2006-02-02|access-date=2018-10-22|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Final years of publishing==\nIn the 1990s, the magazine's circulation slumped and it was overtaken by the [[BBC]]'s spin off magazine ''[[Top of the Pops (magazine)|Top of the Pops]]''. [[Emap]]'s other biweekly teen magazine of the period ''[[Big! Magazine|Big!]]'' (which featured more celebrities and stars of TV series including Australians based ''[[Home and Away]]'' and United States imported ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]'') was closed and this celeb focus was shifted over to ''Smash Hits'', which became less focused on [[teen pop]] and more of an entertainment magazine. The magazine also shifted size a number of times in subsequent relaunches including one format that was as big as an album with songwords to be clipped out on the card cover. Television presenter and journalist [[Kate Thornton]] was editor for a short time.\n\nIn February 2006, it was announced that the magazine would cease publication after the February 13 edition due to declining sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4673136.stm|title=Smash Hits magazine closing down|work=BBC News|date=2 February 2006|accessdate=22 March 2014}}</ref> The digital music video channel, digital radio, and website services still continue.\n\nIn July 2009, a one-off commemorative issue of the magazine was published as a tribute to singer [[Michael Jackson]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090706131423/http://uk.news.yahoo.com/21/20090703/ten-smash-hits-resurrected-for-jackson-5f8abb3.html Smash Hits resurrected for Jackson], ''[[Yahoo|Yahoo News]]'', Retrieved 4 July 2009</ref> Further one-off specials were released in November 2009 ([[Take That]]), December 2010 ([[Lady Gaga]])<ref>[http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1043483&c=1 Smash Hits returns for GaGa special] ''Music Week''.</ref> and November 2019 ([[Max Martin]]), the latter was a free magazine at certain [[London Underground]] stations to mark the debut of Martin's West End musical ''[[& Juliet]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bauermedia.co.uk/newsroom/press-releases/smash-hits-returns-a-one-off-special-of-the-iconic-music-magazine-to-be-published|title=SMASH HITS RETURNS: A ONE-OFF SPECIAL OF THE ICONIC MUSIC MAGAZINE TO BE PUBLISHED|work=[[Bauer Media Group]]|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Editors ==\n\n*\"Chris Hall\" (pseudonym of Nick Logan, who refused to use his name as editor, instead inventing the name from those of his children, Christian and Hallie)\n*Ian Cranna\n*[[David Hepworth]]\n*[[Mark Ellen]]\n*Steve Bush\n*[[Barry McIlheney]]\n*Richard Lowe\n*Mike Soutar\n*Mark Frith\n*[[Kate Thornton]]\n*Gavin Reeve\n*John McKie\n*[[Emma Jones (journalist)|Emma Jones]]\n*Lisa Smosarski\n*Lara Palamoudian\n\n==Compilation albums==\n[[EMAP]] licensed the brand for a number of compilation albums, including a tie in with the ''[[Now That's What I Call Music]]'' brand for ''[[Now Smash Hits]]'', a retrospective of the early 1980s (80 - 87).\n\n==Australian edition==\nThe Australian edition of ''Smash Hits'' magazine began in November 1984 as a fortnightly. The magazine blended some content from the parent publication with locally generated material. Australian ''Smash Hits'' was originally published by [[Fairfax Media|Fairfax Magazines]] and was later purchased by Mason Stewart Publications. Over the years it became a monthly and then a bi-monthly. In 2007 the magazine retailed for [[Australian dollar|A$]]5.95 Inc. [[Goods and Services Tax (Australia)|GST]] and [[New Zealand dollar|NZ$]]6.50. On 30 March 2007 it was announced that the Australian edition would cease publication due to low readership.<ref>[http://www.bandt.com.au/news/11/0c04af11.asp Emap - Emap shuts Smash Hits after 23 years<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214021938/http://www.bandt.com.au/news/11/0c04af11.asp |date=14 February 2009 }}</ref> The editor at that time was Emma Bradshaw. The issue that was scheduled to be released on 9 May 2007 was cancelled.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Smash Hits (TV channel)]]\n* [[The Hits]]\n* ''[[Number One (magazine)|Number One]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/arts/features/story/0,,1701290,00.html ''Guardian'' Culture Vulture on the demise of ''Smash Hits'']\n\n[[Category:1978 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2006 disestablishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British music magazines]]\n[[Category:Bauer Group (UK)]]\n[[Category:British biweekly magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1978]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 2006]]\n", "name_user": "SnapSnap", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smash_Hits"}
